paragraphs.text:
%md

Steps to create a sample ETL pipeling in fluirengine to calculate CTR by banner pos and hour

1. create pipeline avazutrainETL using sink "avazutraindataparquetsink" 2. add transform node "impression" --> "select * from avazutraindataparquetsink" 3. add trigger node "avazucrtbybannerpos" --> "select banner_pos, sum(case when click = 1 then 1 else 0 end) / (count(1) * 1.0) as CTR from impression group by 1 order by 1" 4. form output sink avazucrtbybannerpossink 4. add trigger node "avazuctrbyhour" --> "select substr(hour, 7) as hour, sum(case when click = 1 then 1 else 0 end) / (count(1) * 1.0) as CTR from impression group by 1 order by 1" 5. form output sink avazuctrbyhoursink

msg.data:
Steps to create a sample ETL pipeling in fluirengine to calculate CTR by banner pos and hour

  1. create pipeline avazutrainETL using sink “avazutraindataparquetsink”
  2. add transform node “impression” –> “select * from avazutraindataparquetsink”
  3. add trigger node “avazucrtbybannerpos” –> “select banner_pos, sum(case when click = 1 then 1 else 0 end) / (count(1) * 1.0) as CTR from impression group by 1 order by 1”
  4. form output sink avazucrtbybannerpossink
  5. add trigger node “avazuctrbyhour” –> “select substr(hour, 7) as hour, sum(case when click = 1 then 1 else 0 end) / (count(1) * 1.0) as CTR from impression group by 1 order by 1”
  6. form output sink avazuctrbyhoursink

convert our data into features for input to a machine learning algorithm

msg.data: convert our data into features for input to a machine learning algorithm

paragraphs.text:
%pyspark
from pyspark.sql.functions import *
strCols = map(lambda t: t[0], filter(lambda t: t[1] == 'string', impression.dtypes))
intCols = map(lambda t: t[0], filter(lambda t: t[1] == 'int', impression.dtypes))
# [row_idx][json_idx]
strColsCount = sorted(map(lambda c: (c, impression.select(countDistinct(c)).collect()[0][0]), strCols), key=lambda x: x[1], reverse=True)
intColsCount = sorted(map(lambda c: (c, impression.select(countDistinct(c)).collect()[0][0]), intCols), key=lambda x: x[1], reverse=True)
print("strColsCount: {0}\nintColsCount: {1}".format(strColsCount, intColsCount))

paragraphs.text:
%pyspark
# Include PySpark Feature Engineering methods
from pyspark.ml.feature import StringIndexer, VectorAssembler

# All of the columns (string or integer) are categorical columns
maxBins = 70
categorical = map(lambda c: c[0], 
filter(lambda c: c[1] <= maxBins, strColsCount))
categorical += map(lambda c: c[0], 
filter(lambda c: c[1] <= maxBins, intColsCount))


# remove 'click' which we are trying to predict
categorical.remove('click')

print("categorical: {0}".format(categorical))

# Apply string indexer to all of the categorical columns
#  And add _idx to the column name to indicate the index of the
#  categorical value
stringIndexers = map(lambda c: StringIndexer(inputCol = c, outputCol = c + "_idx"), categorical)
#print("stringIndexers: {0}".format(stringIndexers))

# Assemble the put as the input to the VectorAssembler 
#   with the output being our features
assemblerInputs = map(lambda c: c + "_idx", categorical)
print("assemblerInputs: {0}".format(assemblerInputs))
vectorAssembler = VectorAssembler(inputCols = assemblerInputs, outputCol = "features")
#print("vectorAssembler: {0}".format(vectorAssembler))

# The [click] column is our label 
labelStringIndexer = StringIndexer(inputCol = "click", outputCol = "label")

# The stages of our ML pipeline 
stages = stringIndexers + [vectorAssembler, labelStringIndexer]
#print("stages: {0}".format(stages))

%pyspark
from pyspark.ml import Pipeline 
# Create our pipeline 
pipeline = Pipeline(stages = stages) 
# create transformer to add features 
featurizer = pipeline.fit(impression)

%pyspark
# dataframe with feature and intermediate transformation columns appended featurized
featurizedImpressions = featurizer.transform(impression)

%pyspark
df = featurizedImpressions.select('features', 'label')
df.show()

 we will train, predict, and evaluate our model using the GBTClassifier

paragraphs.text:
%pyspark
from pyspark.ml.classification import GBTClassifier
# Train our GBTClassifier model
classifier = GBTClassifier(labelCol="label", featuresCol="features", maxBins=maxBins, maxDepth=10, maxIter=10)
model = classifier.fit(train)

paragraphs.text:
%pyspark
import json
features = map(lambda c: str(json.loads(json.dumps(c))['name']), predictions.schema['features'].metadata.get('ml_attr').get('attrs').values()[0])

#convert numpy.float64 to str for spark.createDataFrame()
weights=map(lambda w: '%.10f' % w, model.featureImportances)
weightedFeatures = sorted(zip(weights, features), key=lambda x: x[1], reverse=True)
spark.createDataFrame(weightedFeatures).toDF("weight", "feature").createOrReplaceTempView('wf')
